Get Smart. A visual correlation of mortality, education and freedom.¶

CMSC320 Final Tutorial¶

Aaron Shavolian¶

Have you ever wondered what the relationship between mortality, educational attainment and freedom looks like in different countries? here we seek to answer this question by collecting and analysing data from reliable sources such as the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the Human Freedom Index (HFI). We will then present this data in a visual representation, allowing viewers to gain valuable insight into how these three factors are linked. Join us on this journey as we explore the correlation between mortality, education and freedom in countries around the world!

Oops!¶

As we can see, the death rates are too high to compare with the freedom and education rates, so we need to scale the death rates according to the population of the country in order to see the correlation between these variables

Convert deaths to mortality rate¶

We need to import a population dataset so that we can adjust our mortality rate. We have observed that the values for deaths are much larger compared to the values for freedom rate and education rate.

Visualize our data using scatter plots¶

Here we are using the scatter plots to show the Rates of freedom,education and mortality according to the country_code. A scatterplot is a type of data display that shows the relationship between two numerical variables. Each member of the dataset gets plotted as a point whose (x, y)(x,y)left parenthesis, x, comma, y, right parenthesis coordinates relates to its values for the two variables.

Checking the Correlation
In this step we check the correlation of the freedom,education and mortalitywith a correlation matrix. Obviously, we want to use the cleaned data to conduct this analysis, so we use our 'df' dataframe as to not include data that we have dropped from the dataframe. We also can ignore the diagonal through the center because we do not need to pay attention to the correlation between a variable and itself. We are left with a sort of heat map where lighter colors describe higher correlations and deeper colors describe lower correlations. From this data, we can tell that bmi and age are correlated heavily, as well as glucose level and age. We can tell from this data that age might play a significant role in whether or not someone has a stroke.

Linear Regression

Linear regression is a commonly used method for analyzing the relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables. The goal of regression is to assess whether the independent variables are good predictors of the dependent variable and to identify which independent variables have a significant impact on the dependent variable, as indicated by the magnitude and sign of the beta estimates. The regression equation is expressed as y = c + b*x, where y is the predicted value of the dependent variable, c is a constant, b is the regression coefficient, and x is the value of the independent variable. The dependent variable may also be referred to as the outcome variable, criterion variable, endogenous variable, or regressand, while the independent variables may be called exogenous variables, predictor variables, or regressors.

Lasso Regression
Lasso is a modification of linear regression, where the model is penalized for the sum of absolute values of the weights. The absolute values of weight will be (in general) reduced, and many will tend to be zeros.

In [85]:

f,ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(14,6))
import scipy as sp
_,(_,_,r)= sp.stats.probplot((y_test-predicted),fit=True,plot=ax[0])
ax[0].set_title('Check for Multivariate Normality: \nQ-Q Plot')

#Check for Homoscedasticity
sns.scatterplot(y = (y_test-predicted), x= predicted, ax = ax[1],color='r') 
ax[1].set_title('Check for Homoscedasticity: \nResidual Vs Predicted');

Relationship
The Seaborn Pairplot allows us to visualize the pairwise relationships between variables within a dataset. This is useful for understanding the data by summarizing a large amount of information in a single figure. It is especially helpful when exploring a dataset and trying to get a sense of its contents.

Conclusion¶

The results show a strong correlation between freedom and education. This means that as freedom increases, education also increases, and vice versa. However, mortality tends to decrease with increases in both freedom and education. This inverse relationship between mortality and freedom and education is not as clear as the positive relationship between freedom and education.
